normalizePath() only decodes unreserved chars (ALPHA, DIGIT, -, ., _, ~) via decodeUnreserved()
Slash '%2f' is NOT decoded by decodeUnreserved (0x2f not in unreserved list)
So '%2f' survives first removeDots, then urlDecode converts it to literal '/', then second removeDots catches it.

However, double-encoded '%252e' path:
- normalizePath: %25 is not unreserved, stays as %25; result: '/%252e%252e/etc/passwd' 
- urlDecode: %25→%, result: '/%2e%2e/etc/passwd'
- removeDots: looks for '/../' but finds '/%2e%2e/' - NO MATCH, passes through!
- getFile produces: 'webroot/%2e%2e/etc/passwd'

The OS filesystem likely won't interpret %2e as '.' so this doesn't escape at the OS level in most cases, but demonstrates the lack of containment check.

